cess being recorded for continuous improvement of the system. Overall, the LLM functions as a versatile engine for reasoning, generation, augmentation, and evaluation across all stages of modern RAG architectures.", "refusal": null, "role": "assistant", "annotations": null, "audio": null, "function_call": null, "tool_calls": null, "provider_specific_fields": {"refusal": null}}, "provider_specific_fields": {}}], "created": 1783472137, "model": "deepseek-v4-flash", "object": "chat.completion", "service_tier": null, "system_fingerprint": "fp_8b330d02d0_prod0820_fp8_kvcache_20260402", "usage": {"completion_tokens": 350, "prompt_tokens": 330, "total_tokens": 680, "completion_tokens_details": null, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": null, "cached_tokens": 0}, "prompt_cache_hit_tokens": 0, "prompt_cache_miss_tokens": 330}, "formatted_response": null, "content": "In the context of advanced retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) systems and related architectures, the Large Language Model (LLM) serves as the central processing and generation component. The LLM is responsible for receiving and processing fused results from both graph queries and vector retrieval, effectively integrating structured and unstructured data to inform its outputs. It is also tasked with scoring and judging the relevance of each retrieved chunk, playing a critical role in filtering and ranking information before generating final answers. Within the CRAG (Corrective Retrieval Augmented Generation) framework specifically, the LLM evaluates retrieved content and decides on the most appropriate response.\n\nBeyond retrieval and evaluation, the LLM is heavily utilized in document augmentation and preprocessing stages. It can preprocess documents by generating summaries, extracting keywords, and creating question-answer pairs, thereby enriching the knowledge base for more efficient downstream retrieval. Additionally, the LLM is employed to rewrite summaries or extract key content from multiple chunks,